\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {L1 score distribution histograms.} Blue = non-watermarked; orange = watermarked. Clear bimodal separation = high AUC. Under no\_attack, both configurations show clean separation. Under rotation\_75 and crop\_0.5, Baseline distributions heavily overlap; MR-AllChan maintains meaningful separation. Under gaussian\_noise\_0.1, all approaches show overlapping distributions with similar gap sizes, confirming it as the remaining open challenge.}}{23}{figure.caption.24}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:hist}{{9}{23}{\textbf {L1 score distribution histograms.} Blue = non-watermarked; orange = watermarked. Clear bimodal separation = high AUC. Under no\_attack, both configurations show clean separation. Under rotation\_75 and crop\_0.5, Baseline distributions heavily overlap; MR-AllChan maintains meaningful separation. Under gaussian\_noise\_0.1, all approaches show overlapping distributions with similar gap sizes, confirming it as the remaining open challenge}{figure.caption.24}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Mean L1 score gap} (non-watermarked minus watermarked) per attack. Larger gaps correlate with higher AUC. MR-AllChan (rightmost bar) maintains the largest gap on geometric attacks while matching others on photometric attacks.}}{23}{figure.caption.25}\protected@file@percent }
